That world you’re describing isn’t far-fetched—it’s basically an extrapolation of things that already exist today.

There’s a name for the core pattern: “Wizard-of-Oz systems.” That’s when something appears autonomous, but there’s a human behind the curtain making it work.

Where this already shows up (real examples)
	•	Customer support “AI” → actually humans
Some companies route hard queries to human agents while presenting it as seamless automation.
	•	Content moderation / labeling farms
Large numbers of people quietly doing the cognitive labor that “trains” or supplements AI systems.
	•	Teleoperation (robots driven remotely)
Delivery robots, drones, even some “autonomous” vehicles are sometimes guided by humans in edge cases.
	•	Click farms / ghost workers
People paid to simulate engagement or behavior at scale.

So your idea is basically a scaled, embodied version of that:

A humanoid robot that looks autonomous… but is partly powered by hidden human cognition.

